#note: See @bib{fromebllab0044@142}: “The Sumerogram @akk{SIM} for @i{simmu} “wound, lesion” is presumably an extra-linguistic adaptation of the Akkadian loan into Sumerian @sux{simₓ(GIG)-ma}, which is attested several times in Sumerian literary contexts (see @bib{Attinger2021Glossaire@924}) and also as the Sumerogram @akk{GIG} = @i{simmu} (see @bib{RN1703@55}; @bib{scheyhing2011babylonisch@81}; @bib{RN2123@492 ad 1}). Perhaps the use of @akk{NAM} = @i{sim} arose in order to disambiguate it from the pervasive @akk{GIG} = @i{marṣu} by resorting to a lexemically unrelated but better-known homophone that was used to render the Akkadian word as a CVC sign.”
